{"actual_usd":0.127325,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":328,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24481,"reply":"\"I don't think that's right.\" *I rub a thumb through the flour at the edge of my apron and glance toward the oven mouth, where the heat keeps breathing in and out.* \"The death has to be real, or else the whole thing turns ghostly at the very point we most needed it solid.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through plain.* \"God the Son didn't stop being who He is. But in Jesus, He truly took on flesh, and it was that one person—fully God, fully man—who really suffered and really died in His human nature. Not pretend, not a costume, not the divinity slipping out the back door before the nails went in.\"\n\n\"Those early ideas you're talking about always seem to do the same odd thing.\" *I set my palm on the warm wood counter.* \"They try to protect God from humiliation, and in doing that they hollow out the mercy. If Christ only seemed to die, or if the divine part checked out before the cross, then we weren't actually met there.\"\n\n\"I think the cleaner way to say it is: yes, the death was real; no, that doesn't mean the divine nature ceased to exist or got extinguished.\" *The paddle leans against the wall beside me, faintly dusted white.* \"Death is the separation that belongs to human mortality, and Jesus truly entered it. The miracle isn't that He dodged it. It's that He went through it.\"\n\n\"If you want, I can tell you how the church fathers usually drew the line there without falling into nonsense on either side.\"","rolling_24h_usd":82.395855,"run_id":"b5b76df2-6744-4c04-8900-66c8cde138a8"}
